<body>
<h1>Reproducible Research: Peer Assessment 1</h1>

<h3>Introduction from <a href="https://github.com/rdpeng/RepData_PeerAssessment1">repo</a>.</h3>

<p>It is now possible to collect a large amount of data about personal
movement using activity monitoring devices such as a
<a href="http://www.fitbit.com">Fitbit</a>, <a href="http://www.nike.com/us/en_us/c/nikeplus-fuelband">Nike
Fuelband</a>, or
<a href="https://jawbone.com/up">Jawbone Up</a>. These type of devices are part of
the &ldquo;quantified self&rdquo; movement &ndash; a group of enthusiasts who take
measurements about themselves regularly to improve their health, to
find patterns in their behavior, or because they are tech geeks. But
these data remain under-utilized both because the raw data are hard to
obtain and there is a lack of statistical methods and software for
processing and interpreting the data.</p>

<p>This assignment makes use of data from a personal activity monitoring
device. This device collects data at 5 minute intervals through out the
day. The data consists of two months of data from an anonymous
individual collected during the months of October and November, 2012
and include the number of steps taken in 5 minute intervals each day.</p>

<p>The document was produced with <strong>R version 3.1.2 at a i686-pc-linux-gnu (32-bit) Ubuntu</strong>, also we settled the local time -  <em>it shall be resettled in the end</em> - and global options for knitr:  </p>

<pre><code class="r">knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo=TRUE)
local &lt;- Sys.getlocale(category = &quot;LC_TIME&quot;)
Sys.setlocale(&quot;LC_TIME&quot;, &quot;en_US.UTF-8&quot;)
</code></pre>

<h3>Loading and preprocessing the data</h3>

<p>We traded <code>https</code> for <code>http</code> to download and unzip the file on this operating system from <a href="https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/repdata%2Fdata%2Factivity.zip">link</a>. </p>

<pre><code class="r">workdir &lt;- getwd()
download.file(&quot;http://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/repdata%2Fdata%2Factivity.zip&quot;
              ,destfile=&quot;zipado.zip&quot;)
unzip(zipfile=&quot;zipado.zip&quot;, files = NULL, list = FALSE, overwrite = TRUE,
      junkpaths = FALSE, exdir = workdir, unzip = &quot;internal&quot;,
      setTimes = FALSE)
data_original &lt;- tbl_df(read.csv(&quot;activity.csv&quot;, header = TRUE, sep = &quot;,&quot;))
time &lt;- format(Sys.time(),&quot;%a %b %d %X %Y&quot;)
</code></pre>

<p>The current time is Sun Jan 18 06:46:46 PM 2015.</p>

<h3>What is mean total number of steps taken per day?</h3>

<p>I ignored the missing values as recommended for two following tasks: </p>

<ul>
<li><p>Make a histogram of the total number of steps taken each day  </p></li>
<li><p>Calculate and report the mean and median total number of steps taken per day  </p></li>

<pre><code class="r">data1 &lt;- data_original
data1$date %&lt;&gt;% ymd

mediana &lt;- median(sum_data1$total_steps,na.rm=TRUE)

<p>Our calculations: the <strong>mean</strong> 10766 $\pm $ 4269 or in another notation 10800(4300) total number of steps taken per day and <strong>median</strong> 10765 total number of steps taken per day. See the following histogram:</p>

<pre><code class="r">titulo &lt;- paste(&quot;Total Steps per Day: vertical line at median=&quot;,mediana,&quot;.&quot;)

<h3>What is the average daily activity pattern?</h3>

<p>Two tasks: </p>

<ul>

<pre><code class="r">meansteps_byinterval&lt;-data1%&gt;%group_by(interval) %&gt;%

<h3>Imputing missing values</h3>

<pre><code class="r">NA_number &lt;- sum(is.na(data1[,1]))
</code></pre>

<p>We have 2304 <em>NAs</em> at variable <strong>steps</strong> of original data and the presence of missing days may introduce bias into some calculations or summaries of the data.</p>

<p>We filled in the missing values of <strong>steps</strong> in the new dataset <strong>data2</strong> with the 5-minute interval means for influence each interval homogeneously. We calculated these means with all <strong>steps</strong>&#39; values for each interval of all days.</p>

<pre><code class="r">data1 %&lt;&gt;% mutate(flag_NA=is.na(steps)) 
data2 &lt;- inner_join(data1, meansteps_byinterval, by = &quot;interval&quot;)       
for(i in 1:17568){
        if(data2[i,4]==TRUE){
                data2[i,1] &lt;- data2[i,5]
                }
        }
sum_data2  &lt;- data2 %&gt;%
                group_by(date) %&gt;%
                        summarize(total_steps=sum(steps))
media2 &lt;- mean(sum_data2$total_steps,na.rm=TRUE)
desvio_padrao2 &lt;- sd(sum_data2$total_steps,na.rm=TRUE)
mediana2 &lt;- median(sum_data2$total_steps,na.rm=TRUE)
z_test &lt;- (media2-media)/sqrt(desvio_padrao^2+desvio_padrao2^2)
</code></pre>

<p>We maked a new data&#39;s histogram with a vertical line at median 10766 steps per day</p>

<pre><code class="r">titulo &lt;- paste(&quot;Total Steps per Day: vertical line at median=&quot;,format(mediana2,digits=5),&quot;.&quot;)
ggplot(sum_data2,aes(x=total_steps))+
geom_histogram(binwidth = 800,fill = &quot;green&quot;)+
geom_vline(data=sum_data2,aes(xintercept = mediana2))+
xlab(&quot;Total Steps per Day&quot;)+
ylab(&quot;Frequency&quot;)+
ggtitle(titulo)
</code></pre>

<h3>Are there differences in activity patterns between weekdays and weekends?</h3>

<p>As recomended for this part we used the weekdays() function and <strong>data2</strong> that is a dataset with the filled-in missing values for this part. Also we created a new factor variable named <strong>week</strong> in this dataset with two levels – <em>“weekday”</em> and <em>“weekend”</em> - indicating whether a given date is a weekday or weekend day. </p>

<pre><code class="r">data2 %&lt;&gt;% mutate(week=&quot;weekday&quot;)
for(i in 1:17568){
        if((weekdays(data2$date[i])==&quot;Sunday&quot;) | (weekdays(data2$date[i])==&quot;Saturday&quot;)){
                data2$week[i] &lt;- &quot;weekend&quot;
                }
        } 
data2$week %&lt;&gt;% as.factor
sum_week  &lt;- data2 %&gt;%
                group_by(interval,week) %&gt;%
                        summarize(total_steps=sum(steps)) 

sum_weekend &lt;- sum_week %&gt;%
                        filter(week==&quot;weekend&quot;)
auc_weekend &lt;- -1*trapz(sum_weekend$total_steps,sum_weekend$interval)

sum_weekday &lt;- sum_week %&gt;%
                        filter(week==&quot;weekday&quot;)
auc_weekday &lt;- -1*trapz(sum_weekday$total_steps,sum_weekday$interval)

activity_diff &lt;- 100*auc_weekend/auc_weekday
</code></pre>

<p>We maked a panel plot containing a time series plot of the 5-minute interval (x-axis) and the total number of steps taken, averaged across all weekday days or weekend days (y-axis):</p>

<pre><code class="r">titulo &lt;- paste(&quot;Total Steps per Interval: grouped by weekend X weekday.&quot;)
ggplot(sum_week,aes(x=interval,y=total_steps))+
geom_line()+
facet_grid(week~.)+
xlab(&quot;Intervals&quot;)+
ylab(&quot;Total Steps per Interval&quot;)+
ggtitle(titulo)
</code></pre>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt=""/> </p>

<p>We can see that there was a similar variation of the circadian-like cycle in both groups; this similarity was much higher in those rest periods.</p>

<p>The activity was higher on weekdays: unlike the weekend whose peaks hardly reached 2500 steps per interval; those of weekdays activity peaks often passing the limit of 2500 and sometimes exceeded the barrier of 10,000 steps per interval.</p>

<p>The areas under curves on this plot is another way to measure activity. The weekend activity is only  44.5%  of weekday activity.</p>

<p>At least we maked a panel plot containing a time series plot of the 5-minute interval (x-axis) and the average number of steps taken, averaged across all weekday days or weekend days (y-axis):</p>

<pre><code class="r">mean_week  &lt;- data2 %&gt;%
                group_by(interval,week) %&gt;%
                        summarize(mean_steps=mean(steps))

mean_weekend &lt;- mean_week %&gt;%
                        filter(week==&quot;weekend&quot;)
auc_weekend2 &lt;- -1*trapz(mean_weekend$mean_steps,mean_weekend$interval)

mean_weekday &lt;- mean_week %&gt;%
                        filter(week==&quot;weekday&quot;)
auc_weekday2 &lt;- -1*trapz(mean_weekday$mean_steps,mean_weekday$interval)

activity_diff2 &lt;- 100*auc_weekday2/auc_weekend2
</code></pre>

<p>Pay attention to following plot:</p>

<pre><code class="r">titulo &lt;- paste(&quot;Mean Steps per Interval: grouped by weekend X weekday.&quot;)
ggplot(mean_week,aes(x=interval,y=mean_steps))+
geom_line()+
facet_grid(week~.)+
xlab(&quot;Intervals&quot;)+
ylab(&quot;Mean Steps per Interval&quot;)+
ggtitle(titulo)
</code></pre>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt=""/> </p>

<p>We can see that there was a more similar variation of the circadian-like cycle in both averaged groups than added groups and as well the similarity in those rest periods. We used the areas under curves to measure activity and the mean weekday activity is 79.9%  of mean weekend activity without improvement in the ability to differentiate.</p>

<p>The weekday averaged activity was similar to weekend one and this left me with more unanswered questions. What kind of activity is the most beneficial for health: the more regular or one that is more extensive? This device with another accompaniments together can discern the effects of different lifestyles, some more phasic and anothers more regular&hellip; Anyway the accumulated activity has improved the rating of the activities on weekends and on weekdays. At least the weekend had had two days and weekdays five, so the averaged groups&#39; evaluation can be more precise.</p>
